    "is_good_patch": true,
    "synth_pr": "\n## Title: Fix L1_stats_thread crash due to uninitialized frame counters\n\n### Summary\nThe L1_stats_thread in the LTE eNB executable was accessing uninitialized memory when trying to read frame_tx values from the L1_proc_tx structure. This caused segmentation faults and unpredictable behavior when the statistics thread was enabled.\n\nThe issue occurred because the frame and subframe counters in both L1_proc and L1_proc_tx structures were not explicitly initialized to zero during the eNB initialization phase. When the L1_stats_thread started before the L1 processing threads had a chance to update these counters, it would read garbage values, leading to crashes in the dump_ulsch_stats and dump_uci_stats functions.\n\n### Reproduction Steps\n1. Start the LTE eNB with statistics enabled (ensure IS_SOFTMODEM_NOSTATS_BIT is not set)\n2. Enable the L1_stats_thread by not setting the NOSTATS flag\n3. Observe segmentation fault or invalid memory access in the L1_stats.log file\n4. The crash typically occurs within the first few seconds of eNB operation\n\n### Changes\n- `executables/lte-enb.c`: Added explicit initialization of all frame and subframe counters (frame_tx, subframe_tx, frame_rx, subframe_rx, and PRACH related counters) for both L1_proc and L1_proc_tx structures during the init_eNB_proc function\n- `executables/lte-enb.c`: Added safety check in L1_stats_thread to validate frame_tx values before passing them to dump functions, with fallback to frame 0 if values are invalid\n"
}